{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}} {{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}
The New South Wales '''Health Care Complaints Commission''' (commonly referred to as the {{'}}'''HCCC'''{{'}}), is an independent [[Statutory authority|statutory body]] created by the [[Parliament of New South Wales]], [[Australia]] to receive, assess, resolve or prosecute complaints relating to [[Health professional|health service providers]] in New South Wales.<ref name="NSWLegislature">''Health Care Complaints Act'' (NSW) 1993, s3, current version for 4 July 2014 to date (accessed 13 January 2015 at 12:32): http://www.legislation.nsw.gov.au/maintop/view/inforce/act+105+1993+cd+0+N</ref>
== Purpose == The Health Care Complaints Commission's purpose is stated in the [http://legislation.nsw.gov.au/#/view/act/1993/105 ''Health Care Complaints Act 1993 ''(NSW)] which establishes it as "protection of the health and safety of the public must be the paramount consideration".<ref name="NSWLegislature"/>
The Commission receives consistent media attention for its actions. Recent attention includes criticism of its performance with a major [[Sydney]] newspaper, the ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]], ''reporting that new "statistics expos[ed] a dramatic decline in investigations despite complaints from the public being at an all-time high."<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/health-care-complaints-commission-in-crisis-20140619-zsem0.html|title = Health Care Complaints Commission in Crisis|date = 20 June 2014|accessdate = 13 January 2015|website = The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher = The Sydney Morning Herald|last = Duff|first = Eamon}}</ref>
== History == The Health Care Complaints Commission was formed in 1994 after the [[Chelmsford Royal Commission]] which investigated the 'deep sleep therapy' performed at the Chelmsford Hospital in Sydney.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}
